            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Akira Yamamoto\u2019s life began in the foggy avenues of San Francisco\u2019s Outer Richmond, the quiet son of Japanese immigrants. His father, a stoic gardener, valued practicality and stability, while his mother harbored a quiet love for ikebana and watercolor she rarely had time to indulge. From a young age, Akira was an observer, communicating more through his detailed sketches in worn notebooks than with words. His parents hoped he would pursue a career in business or engineering, and for two years at SF State, he tried to fit that mold.\n\nThe turning point came during a volunteer stint at a community center in the Mission District. He witnessed firsthand how a simple art project could unlock the voice of a traumatized child who had refused to speak to counselors. In that moment, Akira saw his future. He changed his major to psychology and art, a decision that created a rift with his father that would take years to heal. He later earned his graduate degree in Art Therapy, committed to bridging the gap between creative expression and mental well-being.\n\nHis career grew organically from the city's needs. He started as a clinical therapist working with at-risk youth in the Bayview, then expanded his practice to include seniors grappling with dementia in Japantown. His calm demeanor and profound empathy, combined with his father\u2019s pragmatism, made him an effective leader. He was eventually promoted to Program Director, where he now oversees therapeutic arts initiatives across healthcare and social assistance programs.\n\nNow 53, Akira lives a settled life in Cole Valley with his partner of fifteen years, a landscape architect named David. His daily 3.8-mile commute on the N-Judah is a cherished ritual\u2014a time to decompress, sketch fellow passengers, or simply watch the city slide by. His connection to San Francisco is etched into his work and his soul; he serves the communities that raised him. His dream is no longer about proving his path was the right one, but about ensuring the programs he built will outlast him. He hopes to mentor a new generation of therapists and, perhaps, finally find time to rediscover his own art, not as a tool for healing others, but as a simple, personal joy."
        },
        {
            "@type": "PropertyValue",
            "name": "reveries",
            "value": "1.\nHe remembers the scent of damp earth and trimmed juniper. He was eight, watching his father work in the foggy garden of their Outer Richmond home. His father\u2019s hands were calloused but precise, finding the perfect line in a gnarled branch. Akira tried showing him a drawing of a bird, but his father only grunted, wiping sweat from his brow. It wasn't disapproval, but a language barrier. Akira learned then that his father\u2019s love was pruned and cultivated, not drawn. It taught him that care could be silent and powerfully pragmatic.\n\n2.\nHe was twenty, in a stuffy room at the Mission community center. The girl hadn't spoken in weeks. He just sat with her, offering crayons. One afternoon, she picked up a yellow one and drew a small, wobbly sun above a crude house. He felt a jolt, a current of pure purpose that electrified his being. It wasn't just a drawing; it was a voice. In that silent, crayon-wielding moment, he saw his future\u2014not in numbers or code, but in unlocking human expression. He knew he had to change everything.\n\n3.\nHe was 35, leading an art group for seniors with dementia in Japantown, when his father appeared at the door. Akira\u2019s heart seized. His father didn\u2019t speak, but walked to a woman struggling with a brush and gently steadied her hand, his gardener\u2019s grip now a tool of quiet aid. He looked at Akira and gave a single, slow nod. No apologies were exchanged, but in that shared act of helping another, the years of distance collapsed. It was the proudest moment of his life.\n\n4.\nOn their third date, David unrolled a blueprint in a small cafe in Hayes Valley. It was a plan for a hospital\u2019s healing garden. Akira traced the flowing lines, the thoughtful placement of benches and resilient plants. He saw his father\u2019s pragmatism and his mother\u2019s artistry, but here they were fused with a therapeutic purpose he understood intimately. Looking at David, who was explaining soil acidity with such passion, Akira felt a deep sense of homecoming. He had found someone who spoke both his languages.\n\n5.\nJust last year, rattling home on the N-Judah as it emerged from the Sunset Tunnel, he found himself sketching. Not for work, not to analyze, but just because. He captured the tired slump of a student\u2019s shoulders, the way the late afternoon light hit her headphones. It felt different\u2014lighter. There was no therapeutic goal, no report to write. It was the joy of seeing and the simple pleasure of a graphite line on paper. For the first time in decades, the art felt entirely his own."
